 droves—but they have not abandoned religion. Carolyn Chen spent more than five years in Silicon Valley, conducting a wealth of in-depth interviews and gaining unprecedented access to the best and brightest of the tech world. The result is a penetrating account of how work now satisfies workers’ needs for belonging, identity, purpose, and transcendence that religion once met. Chen argues that tech firms are offering spiritual care such as Buddhist-inspired mindfulness practices to make their employees more productive, but that our religious traditions, communities, and public sphere are paying the price.We all want our jobs to be meaningful and fulfilling. Work Pray Code reveals what can happen when work becomes religion, and when the workplace becomes the institution that shapes our souls.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aCorporate culturezCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 0aEmployeesxReligious life. 0aHigh technology industrieszCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County)xEmployees. 0aReligion in the workplacezCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAmy Cuddy.  aAndy Puddicombe.  aArousal.  aAshram.  aAsian people.  aAsperger syndrome.  aBetterment.  aBuddhism.  aBuddhist meditation.  aBusiness guru.  aCafeteria.  aCareer.  aChristian fraternity.  aCivil Rights Act of 1964.  aCoaching.  aCompetitive advantage.  aDance studio.  aDeity.  aDeregulation.  aDeskilling.  aDharma talk.  aDisruptive innovation.  aDistraction.  aDog park.  aEastern religions.  aEconomics.  aEmployment.  aEnergy medicine.  aEntrepreneurship.  aEquanimity.  aErnst Troeltsch.  aFight-or-flight response.  aFixed asset.  aFunding.  aGermans.  aGod.  aGrandparent.  aGreens R